## What is the current behavior?

Issue Number: http://b/214103351

Angular generates `goog.getMsg()` statements for JSCompiler which do _not_ contain any options.

```html
<div i18n>Hello, {{ name }}!</div>
```

Becomes:

```typescript
const MSG_XXX = goog.getMsg(
  // Message template.
  'Hello, {$interpolation}',
  // Message parameters.
  { interpolation': '...' },
);
```

## What is the new behavior?

Angular generates `goog.getMsg()` statements for JSCompiler which _do_ contain original code in the options. This is useful for identifying specific placeholders which are otherwise named `interpolation`. See http://b/219565887 for discussion of the new `goog.getMsg()` API.

```html
<div i18n>Hello, {{ name }}!</div>
```

Becomes:

```typescript
const MSG_XXX = goog.getMsg(
  // Message template.
  'Hello, {$interpolation}',
  // Message parameters.
  { interpolation': '...' },
  // Message options.
  {
    // Original code for each placeholder.
    original_code: {
      'interpolation': '{{ name }}',
    },
  },
);
```

## Does this PR introduce a breaking change?

- [X] No

## Other information

Existing tests did *not* like this change since it required updating basically every compliance test which included i18n, so most of the PR is just fixing them. Unfortunately, the existing parser for objects in `__i18n*__` macros for tests expects an object with a maximum depth of only one (`{foo: 'bar'}`), while tests containing `original_code` go as deep as *six* (`{foo: {bar: {baz: {...}}}}`). This is compounded by the fact that Angular template evaluation also uses `{{ foo }}` which adds to the depth even though they are in string literals. I updated the object param regular expression to support a maximum of six levels of nesting in the object, which is good enough for now. Longer term we should really replace the system with a proper parser.

